    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument about public services often focuses on the immediate, short-term costs of integration and infrastructure strain, which can feel substantial to local communities. While some immigrants contribute taxes, the initial demand on services like schools and healthcare can create visible, immediate budget pressures. Whether this is a \"net drain\" is highly debated, as long-term tax contributions from immigrants often balance out these upfront costs over time.",
